'''Nea Salamis Famagusta FC''' or '''Nea Salamina Famagusta FC''' ({{lang-el|<U+039D><U+03AD><U+03B1> <U+03A3><U+03B1><U+03BB><U+03B1><U+03BC><U+03AF><U+03C2> <U+0391><U+03BC><U+03BC><U+03BF><U+03C7><U+03CE><U+03C3><U+03C4><U+03BF><U+03C5>}}) is a professional [[Association football|football]] [[Sports club|club]] based in [[Ammochostos]] (also known by its Romanized name: ''Famagusta''), [[Cyprus]]. Since the occupation of the north part of the island through [[Turkish Invasion of Cyprus|invasion by Turkish troops]] in 1974, Nea Salamis is a [[refugee]] team and since then is based in [[Larnaca]].

Nea Salamis's greatest moment is the winning of the [[Cypriot Cup]] and the [[Cyprus FA Shield]] (Super Cup) at 1990. Highest place finished in the [[Cypriot First Division|Cypriot championship]] was third place. The first five years after the foundation (1948-1953), the team participated in the championships of the [[Cyprus Amateur Football Federation]]. In 1953 the club became a member of the [[Cyprus Football Association]] (CFA) participating regularly in championships and cups under the auspices of the federation. The football team has more than 50 participations in the [[Cypriot First Division]], being in seventh place in league's ranking.

The team participated for the first time in European competitions in 1990, at [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], and the next years recorded participation in the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]] ([[UEFA Intertoto Cup 1995|1995]], [[UEFA Intertoto Cup 1997|1997]], and [[UEFA Intertoto Cup 2000|2000]]).

Nea Salamina FC is part of [[Nea Salamina Famagusta]] multi-sport club, which was founded in 1948 and maintains departments for football and volleyball.

==History==
===The early years===
The foundation of the football department is directly connected with the history of the club. At the time of the founding of Nea Salamina, [[Greece]] entered a period of armed conflict due to the conflict between [[leftist]]s and [[rightist]]s in the [[Greek Civil War]]. The situation in Greece moved to Cyprus infiltrating both in political life and in sport<ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref>. <U+039C>ost athletic players also involved in politics. In Famagusta, the Evagoras Gymnastic Association ''GSE'' ({{lang-el|<U+0393><U+03C5><U+03BC><U+03BD><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03C4><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03CC><U+03C2> <U+03A3><U+03CD><U+03BB><U+03BB><U+03BF><U+03B3><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+0395><U+03C5><U+03B1><U+03B3><U+03CC><U+03C1><U+03B1><U+03C2>}}) and [[Anorthosis Famagusta FC]] was the only clubs involved in sports. GSE had many [[leftist]]s athletes in its ranks, who was the champions athletes of Cyprus. In Anorthosis many players were [[leftist]]s. Under the influence of the political climate of the time, both GSE and Anorthosis began to impose restrictions on the admission of [[leftist]]s members<ref name="SAL11">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=97}}</ref><ref name="SAL12"></ref>, or denied promotion players leftist beliefs. Since the beginning of 1947 a group of people of Famagusta with leftist ideas inside and outside GSE and Anorthosis felt that there was room for the creation of another sports club in the city. In front of the restrictions imposed, they envisioned a club that would be away from politics and would appeal to all strata of Famagusta, in order to spread sports<ref name="SAL12">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=16}}</ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref>.

Following deliberations, on 14 February 1948<ref name="SAL1"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref> was the final decision on establishing the club and began efforts to Constituent Assembly and to register members. These efforts brought results and <U+03BF><U+03BD> Sunday, March 7, 1948<ref name="SAL1"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1">{{cite web|url=http://www.famagusta.org.cy/default.asp?id=261 |title=<U+039D><U+0395><U+0391> <U+03A3><U+0391><U+039B><U+0391><U+039C><U+0399><U+039D><U+0391> <U+0391><U+039C><U+039C><U+039F><U+03A7><U+03A9><U+03A3><U+03A4><U+039F><U+03A5> |accessdate=2012-08-02|date=|work=<U+0391><U+03B8><U+03BB><U+03B7><U+03C4><U+03B9><U+03C3><U+03BC><U+03CC><U+03C2> |publisher=Famagusta municipality |language=Greek }}</ref> in the movie "Hadjihambis" Famagusta, the constituent assembly of New Salamis, which was the first leftist club of Cyprus.<ref name="SAL1">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=17}}</ref> After the foundation of the club many expressed desire to join. The football department wasn't strong that period, as no ready footballers had joined.<ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=20}}</ref>

=== Persecution of the GSE Stadium and establishing CAFF ===
Before the Pancyprian athletics in May 1948, [[Hellenic Amateur Athletic Association]] (SEGAS), asked all the Gymnastics Association of Cyprus to state that clubs were "nationalist beliefs"<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref>. The rightists athletic clubs and athletes signed these statements. The only club that refused to sign the statement was the Gymnastic Association "Kinyras" Paphos and therefore excluded from the games. The leftists athletes opposed to the declaration made by the clubs, refused to sign the statement<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref>. Among the first to react were the champions of GSE, Antonys Totsis ({{lang-el|<U+0391><U+03BD><U+03C4><U+03CE><U+03BD><U+03B7><U+03C2> <U+03A4><U+03CC><U+03C4><U+03C3><U+03B7><U+03C2>}}) and Nikis Georgiou ({{lang-el|<U+039D><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03AE><U+03C2> <U+0393><U+03B5><U+03C9><U+03C1><U+03B3><U+03AF><U+03BF><U+03C5>}}). GSE invited the two athletes to apologise but they insisted on their position that sports should stay away from politics. <ref name="GAV19">{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=19}}</ref> In addition, the leftist athletes decided to support the Gymnastic Association "Kinyras" Paphos, if it does not allow to take part in the Pancyprian Games. Although they had many chances to occupy the first positions, they preferred to stand to Kinyras. GSE was characterized as dominant for winning the first position in the competition<ref name="SAL11"></ref>, but after that facts took the third place. Reacting to the fact that athletes of Nea Salamis were not involved in the Pancyprian Games, GSE has sent a letter to the club informing that refused entry to the [[GSE Stadium]]<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref><ref name="GAV19"></ref>, a letter signed by the President of GSE<ref name="SAL13"></ref>. Followed deletions and other athletes from GSE and Anorthosis, who had to stand by their teammates.<ref name="GAV19"></ref> The prohibition on the use of the stadium posed a problem to Nea Salamis, as they were not able to use it to participate in the new soccer league.<ref name="SAL13">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=21}}</ref>

Similar atmosphere against  leftist athletes prevailing in other cities of Cyprus. In Larnaca was founded in April [[Alki Larnaca F.C.]]. Next month, the Gymnastic Club Zeno (GSZ) in general meeting, banned Alki from using [[GSZ Stadium (1928)|GSZ Stadium]].<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="SAL13"></ref><ref name="GAV19"></ref> A similar proposal to exclude Turks and Catholics rejected. At the same general meeting, members of the GSZ, amended the relevant article of the Statute and prohibits future enrollment States if they had previously signed a declaration that "have enclosed them in Greece," virtually prohibiting leftist athletes to be members, or use its stadium.<ref name="GAV19"></ref> In Nicosia was founded in May [[Orfeas Nicosia]]. In the same month [[APOEL F.C.]] sent a telegram to SEGAS, on the occasion of National Games, "cordial brotherly greeting to the entire Greek youth athletes" and wished the stopping of the ethnoktonos mutiny. Leftist members and athletes of APOEL considered "ethnoktonos mutiny" as a challenge and partisan positioning of the club and immediately distanced themselves. The Cypriot press, with constant reports and comments sparked climate<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="SAL13"></ref><ref name="GAV19"></ref>. This was followed by indefinitely punishment of five athletes of APOEL (Lympouris, Tsialis, Gogakis, Xatzivasileiou and Christodoulou) who, along with former members of the APOEL, founded in June 1948 a new club in Nicosia, [[AC Omonia]].<ref name="SAL11"></ref><ref name="SAL13"></ref><ref name="GAV19">{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=19}}</ref> Then, AS [[Kyrenia]] waw founded<ref name="SAL13">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=23}}</ref>.

Due of leftist beliefs of their members, new clubs were not accepted into the ranks of [[Cyprus Football Association]] (CFA) and so proceeded to start a new football federation, the [[Cyprus Amateur Football Federation]] (KEPO) in December 1948 <ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=23}}</ref><ref name="SAL14">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=98}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=51}}</ref>. The new federation, organized leagues and cups<ref name="SAL3">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=140}}</ref>, became the occasion to deal with football thousands of new fans. The matches of CAFF's championship attracted much more fans than those of CFA<ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=24}}</ref><ref name="SAL2">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=141}}</ref>. In CAFF competitions six clubs was participated: Nea Salamis in [[Famagusta]], Omonia and Orpheus in [[Nicosia]], Alki at [[Larnaca]], AMOL at [[Limassol]] (which in 1951 was renamed Antaeus) and Neos Asteras in [[Morphou]]<ref name="SAL3"></ref>.

===Unification of cypriot football===
The clubs members of CAFF favored the unification of Cyprus football. They tried for three consecutive years to convince CFA to accept them as members, but CFA rejected their request.<ref name="GAV19"></ref> Two football federations and two championships in a small country like Cyprus, was something unprecedented. Created economic problems and sports infrastructure. The separation was hampering prospects for progress and development of Cypriot football.<ref name="SAL4">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=142}}</ref><ref name="SAL15"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref><ref name="GAV23">{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=23}}</ref> In addition, the clubs felt that the spirit of sport is the brotherhood and friendship, not segregation and discrimination. The foundation for the unification of Cyprus Football began to enter <U+03C2><U+03B9><U+03C4><U+03B7> the first version of the sports newspaper ''<U+0391><U+03B8><U+03BB><U+03B7><U+03C4><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03AE>'', launched crusade in favor of unification in December 1952. Through the same newspaper first heard voices for consolidation beyond space of CFA (foreign coaches of CFA's clubs). CFA has condemned the statements of its own club's coaches believing that "it was contrary to the spirit of the Federation"<ref name="SAL15"></ref>. The factors of CFA initially kept hostile condemning those who acted in favor of consolidation.<ref name="SAL15"></ref>. In the summer of 1953 nearly all the top players in the sports era advocated unification of Cypriot football. In August 1953, Nea Salamis, Omonia, Alki and Antaeus submitted a joint application to be members of CFA and to joined [[Cyprus First Division]]. The following month, on 19 September 1953, CFA accepted the application<ref name="SAL15"></ref> of Nea Salamis and Omonia for membership in CFA<ref name="SAL9">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=204}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|<U+0393><U+03B1><U+03B2><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03B7><U+03BB><U+03AF><U+03B4><U+03B7>|2001|p=59}}</ref><ref name="SAL15"></ref>. The war, however, of CFA to these clubs continued<ref name=SAL15></ref>. Rejected the application for Alki, Orpheus and Neos Asteras form (two first joined a year later)<ref name=SAL9></ref>, while citing the statute, argued that a team had to participate in [[Cypriot First Division]] and two in [[Cypriot Second Division]]. The clubs of CAFF accepted these conditions in order to finally achieve integration. In a special session of CAFF decided to join [[Cypriot First Division]] Omonia and [[Cypriot Second Division]] Nea Salamina and Antaeus<ref name="SAL15">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=37-41}}</ref>. Following these developments, CAFF disbanded<ref name="SAL4"></ref>. The first game between teams from the two federations held between Nea Salamis and Anorthosis, who met in a friendly game in the [[GSE Stadium]], on September 27, 1953. Presence 5200 fans, the final result was 3-1 in favor of Anorthosis, in a match that newspaper "Sports" featured as a show of superior sportsmanship and brotherhood of fans.<ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=42}}</ref><ref name="SAL10">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=212}}</ref>

===Famagusta Municipal Stadium===
The club did not have a stadium for training after denial of access to the GSE stadium thus initially fled the court of Saint Lukas ("Proodou") in Famagusta<ref name="SAL2"></ref><ref name="SAL7">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=199}}</ref>. In addition, the club began efforts to establish privately owned stadium. In December 1948, [[Israel]] made a [[Gift (law)|donation]] to the municipality of Famagusta three thousand pounds, in gratitude for the help offered by the inhabitants of Famagusta to [[Jews|Jewish]] refugees. The donation was intended to implement a community service project. Gabriel Makris, alderman Famagusta and footballer of Nea Salamina, promoted the association's recommendation to create the field. The city council decided Famagusta "financial assistance granted to the Jews to create Municipal Sports Stadium, which is available to Famagustans for the promotion and spread of mass popular sport." The stadium was available to Nea Salamina and to any club cultivated sports<ref name="SAL8">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=25}}</ref>. In early 1949 started construction with volunteer work<ref name="SAL2"></ref><ref name="SAL7"></ref> the Municipal Stadium, in the parish of Saint John Famagusta. The stadium was completed in 1952 and was the first stadium of Cyprus with a roof in the stands. In the construction of any kind involved with labor supply and the fans of the club, like footballers who worked on its construction.<ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=189}}</ref>. The stadium was completed in 1952 and was the headquarters of Nea Salamina for the period 1952-53<ref name="SAL2"></ref><ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref>. Since 1953, after the unification of football federations established as ground [[GSE Stadium]]<ref name="SAL8"></ref><ref name="SAL10"></ref> until 1974. Due to the occupation of Famagusta by the Turkish army after the [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|Turkish invasion in Cyprus]], the club was forced to move its headquarters. The city's Municipal Stadium was used for training of the team until 1974<ref>{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=78}}</ref>.

===Ammochostos Stadium===
{{Main|Ammochostos Stadium}}

The original home ground of [[Nea Salamis FC]] was [[GSE Stadium]] in [[Famagusta]], but due to the [[Military occupation|Turkish occupation of the town]] since 1974 they cannot use it. From 1974 until 1991 Nea Salamina used [[GSZ Stadium (1928)|GSZ Stadium]] in [[Larnaca]], [[Dasaki Stadium]] in Dasaki Achnas, Municipal Stadium of [[Dherynia]] and [[Antonis Papadopoulos Stadium]] in Larnaca. In 1991, built their own stadium, [[Ammochostos Stadium]].

Ammochostos Stadium has a capacity of 5000 seats and is located in Larnaca. The Ammochostos Stadium mainly used for football matches. Owner of the stadium is Nea Salamina. In the same area is the offices of the club.

Ammochostos Stadium named after the town of Famagusta, which was the original seat of Nea Salamis before the Turkish invasion. Constructed in 1991 and built into the refugee camps of Larnaca. The decision to create the step was taken in 1989 and in December of the same year began the construction. Thanks to the contributions of supporters of Nea Salamis in Cyprus and abroad, [[Cyprus Sports Organisation]] and voluntary work, succeeded in manufacturing in a short period of time.<ref name="<U+0391><U+039C><U+039C>1"></ref><ref name="STIb188">{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=188}}</ref> 

The stadium hosted the 1992 [[UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship|UEFA European Under-16 Football Championship]] final on May 17, 1992 between  [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and [[Spain national football team|Spain]] where Germany won 2-1.<ref name=>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ec-u16-92.html |title=European U-16 Championship 1992 |accessdate=2012-08-02|date=2006-06-28|work= |publisher=RSSSF }}</ref>

The first official game of Nea Salamis Famagusta in tbe stadium was on Saturday, October 12, 1991 with [[Evagoras Paphos]] as opponent. Nea Salamina won 4-1.<ref name="STLb191">{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=191}}</ref>

=== Emblem and colors ===
The emblem of Nea Salamina, just founded, was the [[Olympic flame|torch]]. Completed with the introduction of Reds color, while added to [[shield]] the [[Olympic symbols#flags|five circles]] of the [[Olympic Games]].<ref name="SAL5"></ref>  The first colors of Nea Salamina was yellow and crimson<ref name="SAL6">{{harvnb|Meletiou|2011|p=196}}</ref><ref name="SAL5"/>. Fought with them for two years in the league of [[Cyprus Amateur Football Federation]]. After 1950 the Governing Council decided to establish the red color<ref name="SAL6"/><ref name="SAL5"/>. The recommendation was based on the thought that the red symbolizes the power and the white peace. The Reds jerseys with stripes were preferred because they resembled [[Olympiacos CFP|Olympiakos Piraeus]]<ref name="SAL5">{{harvnb|Stilianou|Neofitou|1988|p=4}}</ref>.

==Competitions==
===Leagues and cups of CAFF===
At five leagues of [[Cyprus Amateur Football Federation]], Nea Salamina failed to win a title. The last two years managed to finish in second place. The 1952-53 season was the cup finalists losing 2-0 to AC Omonia at Gkooul stadium (AC Omonia's ground).

