==== Decade 1990-1999 ====
;Cup winner
The period 1989-1990 was the most successful in the history of the club. Nea Salamina won its first football title, the [[Cypriot Cup]].<ref name=STIb121>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=121}}</ref> This success strongly celebrated by friends of the club. The week before the final was great and unprecedented mobilization among fans of the team, even from abroad, who traveled to Cyprus only to attend the game.<ref name=STIb123>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=123}}</ref> It is worth noting that this title was the second to win a refugee club after the 1974 invasion<ref name=CUP>{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=126}}</ref>. In the final, June 9, 1990, Nea Salamina won Omonia, 3-2 on [[Tsirion Stadium]] in [[Limassol]]. The players who competed in the final was historic: [[Christakis Christofi]], [[Artemis Andreou]], [[Kipros Tsigkelis]], [[Elissaios Psaras]], [[Floros Nicholaou]] (captain), [[Kenny Dyer]], [[Vangelis Adamou]], [[Takis David]], [[Christakis Mavros]], [[Elias Elia]], [[Charalambos Andreou]] (Pambis Andreou) and S. Anastasiou. Scorers were Elias Elias, the Christakis Mavros and Pambis Andreou. Coach was old footballer of Nea Salamina, [[Andreas Mouskallis]]<ref name=CUP></ref><ref name=CUP2>{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=162}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.com.cy/?lang=Gr&show=staticpage&PageID=286&CompetitionID=4 |title=<U+03A4><U+03B5><U+03BB><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03AF> <U+039A><U+03C5><U+03C0><U+03AD><U+03BB><U+03BB><U+03BF><U+03C5> <U+039A><U+03CD><U+03C0><U+03C1><U+03BF><U+03C5> |accessdate=2012-08-03 |date= |work= |publisher=[[Cyprus Football Association]]}}</ref><ref name=STIb125>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=125 |language=Greek}}</ref>.

;Sield winner
Winning the Cup was an opportunity to Salamis to claim the [[LTV Super Cup|Shield]] (Super Cup)<ref name=STIb121></ref>, with the champion rival APOEL. Nea Salamina won 0-1 in [[Makario Stadium]], which was the ground of the opponent<ref name=CUP2></ref>. The goal scorer was Nigel Maknil.<ref name=STIb126>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=126}}</ref>  It was the second title in the history of the club, in only a few months. This year the shield was dedicated to the 30 years of the [[Republic of Cyprus]] (Independence Shield ).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.com.cy/Gr/page/287/49/12/2009%20-%202010 |title=<U+0391><U+03B3><U+03CE><U+03BD><U+03B5><U+03C2>-<U+039A><U+03B1><U+03C4><U+03B1><U+03BA><U+03C4><U+03AE><U+03C3><U+03B5><U+03B9><U+03C2> |accessdate=2012-08-03 |date= |work= |publisher=[[Cyprus Football Association]] |language=Greek}}</ref><ref name=STIb126></ref>

;European participation

As Cup winner, Nea Salamina played for the first time in a European Cup in 1990, which was excluded from the first round by [[Aberdeen F.C.]]. Aberdeen F.C., which had won the [[1982<U+2013>83 European Cup Winners' Cup]] by defeating to the final [[Real Madrid]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/history/season=1982/intro.html|title=1982/83: Aberdeen sing in the rain |accessdate=2012-08-04 |date=2009-01-16 |work=UEFA CUP WINNERS' CUP |publisher=[[UEFA]] |pages= }}</ref>, was a very strong team. The first game was at Tsirion Stadium on September 19, 1990, in the presence of the union 8000 friends. Nea Salamina defeated 0-2 (half time 0-0)<ref name=STEP2>{{harvnb|Stephanidis|2003|p=206}}</ref><ref name="SAL1">{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=157}}</ref><ref name="SAL2">{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ecwc/history/season=1990/round=118/index.html|title=Season 1990 - 1991 |accessdate=2012-07-31 |date=|work=UEFA CUP WINNERS' CUP |publisher=[[UEFA]] |pages= }}</ref>. The replay took place in Aberdeen, being Pintotri on October 3, 1990. Nea Salamina lost 3-0.<ref name=STEP1>{{harvnb|Stephanidis|2003|p=207}}</ref><ref name="SAL1"></ref><ref name="SAL2"></ref> The lineups of the two games was: Christakis Christofi, Artemis Andreou, Kipros Tsigkelis, Elissaios Psaras, Floros Nikolaou, Kenny Dyer, Pambis Andreou, Takis David (68 'Stavros Efthymiou), Nigel Maknil (85' Christakis Mavros), Elias Elias, Vangelis Adamou (home)<ref name=STEP2></ref> and Yiannakis Ioannou, Andreas Artemis, Kipros Tsigkelis, Elissaios Psaras, Floros Nicholaou, Kenny Dyer, Vangelis Adamou, Mavros Christakis, Nigel Maknil (47' Pambis Andreou), Elias Elias, Vassos Mavros (away)<ref name=STEP1></ref>.

The decade 1990-1999 was the most successful in the history of the football department. Apart from winning the cup, shield and participation in the Cup Winners Cup, claimed the championship. An important event is the acquisition of freehold office in 1991, the [[Ammochostos Stadium]] in Larnaca, the construction of which was achieved by volunteer supporters of the club.

During the period [[1992-93 Cypriot First Division|1992-93]] Salamis claimed the championship. At the end of the first round was in the first place<ref name=STIb130>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=130}}</ref> and during the tournament found a difference of up to five points from their rivals.<ref name="GAV132">{{harvnb|Gavreilides|Papamoiseos|2001|p=132}}</ref> Ultimately limited to the third position and the semifinals of the Cup. The same position won in period [[1994-95 Cypriot First Division|1994-95]], ensuring participation in the [[1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup]], became the first cypriot club participated to Intertoto Cup. <ref name=STIb137></ref> At the same time, the player of Nea Salamina [[Charalambos Andreou|Pambis Andreou]] became the league's top scorer with 25 goals.<ref name=STIb137>{{harvnb|Stilianou|1998|p=137}}</ref> Nea Salamis participated in [[1997 UEFA Intertoto Cup]] even though had finished eighth, after other teams have not indicated interest in joining.

